Sign language translation (SLT) remains a challenging task due to the deep modality gap between visual-gestural sign streams and spoken-language text. While recent work has explored variational frameworks—such as conditional VAEs with dual inference paths (prior and posterior)—to improve cross-modal alignment, these models often treat textual integration in the posterior path as an auxiliary conditioning signal without explicitly modeling uncertainty or dynamic attention flow across modalities. The idea of using a shared Attention Residual Gaussian Distribution (ARGD) module, as hinted in Paper 1, is promising but underexplored in terms of how residual attention mechanisms can shape latent distribution learning. My intuition is that instead of merely injecting text into the posterior encoder, we should *dynamically modulate* the structure of the latent space through a shared attention-residual pathway that learns where and how textual context corrects or refines visual representations during inference.

Furthermore, most current approaches either rely on gloss annotations or fail to fully exploit the bidirectional interplay between modalities in the latent space. Gloss-free end-to-end SLT is desirable but suffers from poor semantic grounding. To bridge this, I propose enhancing the posterior path of a VAE not just by conditioning on text, but by integrating a **Shared ARGD Module** that acts as a differentiable, attention-driven residual adapter over latent variables, where the residual signal itself follows a Gaussian distribution whose parameters are jointly influenced by cross-modal attention weights. This creates a stochastic yet structured refinement mechanism: the model learns to attend to relevant parts of the input sequence and applies probabilistic corrections to the prior's latent code based on textual context. Crucially, this module is *shared* across time steps and modalities, enforcing consistency and reducing redundancy.

This approach differs from prior art in three key ways: (1) It moves beyond simple conditioning in the posterior path by introducing a *stochastic attention-residual mechanism* that reshapes the latent distribution; (2) It enables implicit cross-modal alignment without relying on glosses or explicit supervision; and (3) It introduces parameter sharing across attention and distributional components, improving generalization and data efficiency. Unlike XmDA (Paper 3), which uses knowledge distillation via teacher models, or Gloss2Text (Paper 2), which focuses only on the second stage, this method operates within a unified generative framework for true end-to-end gloss-free translation. The result is a more coherent, uncertainty-aware integration of text into visual representation learning—critical for handling the ambiguity inherent in sign language semantics.

